    The root cause of the crash is an integer underflow in the loop             
    termination condition within print_reverse.                                 
                                                                                
    Program State Analysis                                                      
                                                                                
     1 The Loop Termination Condition: The loop is defined as: for (size_t i =  
       v.size() - 1; i >= 0; i--)                                               
        • i is declared as a size_t, which is an unsigned integer type.         
        • When the function is called with an empty vector (empty), v.size()    
          is 0.                                                                 
        • The initialization size_t i = v.size() - 1 results in i = 0 - 1.      
          Since i is an unsigned integer, this causes an underflow, wrapping i  
          around to the maximum possible value for size_t (e.g.,                
          18446744073709551615 on a 64-bit system).                             
        • The loop condition i >= 0 is always true for an unsigned integer,     
          leading the loop to attempt to access memory at v[i] where i is a     
          huge value, causing an out-of-bounds memory access (heap buffer       
          overflow).                                                            
     2 The Defect: Even when the vector is not empty, this loop design is       
       fragile. For v = {10, 20, 30}, i starts at 2. The loop executes for i =  
       2, 1, 0. When i is 0, the loop body executes, and then i-- is            
       performed. 0 - 1 underflows the unsigned size_t variable i, setting it   
       to the maximum size_t value. The loop continues to run infinitely (or    
       until a crash occurs) instead of terminating.                            
                                                                                
    Root Cause                                                                  
                                                                                
    The use of an unsigned integer (size_t) for a loop variable that needs to   
    represent negative values or be compared against 0 in a decrementing loop   
    is a common programming error. In C++, unsigned arithmetic wraps around,    
    and unsigned values can never be less than zero.                            
                                                                                
    Recommendation                                                              
                                                                                
    Minimal Fix                                                                 
                                                                                
    Change the loop to check the condition before decrementing, or use a        
    signed integer (though size_t is preferred for indexing).                   
                                                                                
                                                                                
     static void print_reverse(const std::vector<int>& v) {                     
         if (v.empty()) return; // Handle empty case explicitly                 
         for (size_t i = v.size(); i-- > 0; ) {                                 
             std::printf("%d\n", v[i]);                                         
         }                                                                      
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    Thorough Fix                                                                
                                                                                
    The most robust approach is using reverse iterators, which are              
    specifically designed to handle traversal from the end to the beginning     
    without needing manual index calculation and avoiding underflow issues      
    entirely.                                                                   
                                                                                
                                                                                
     static void print_reverse(const std::vector<int>& v) {                     
         for (auto it = v.rbegin(); it != v.rend(); ++it) {                     
             std::printf("%d\n", *it);                                          
         }                                                                      
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
